      <div class="causes">
        <div> <h3> Causes & Corrections </h3> </div>
        <div class="text-div">
          <p> What we most commonly perceive as Shoulder tension is actually an extension of neck strain from a <a href="/neck-lean">forward leaning head position</a> 
              (sometimes made worse by a <a href="/lowerback-round">rounding of the back</a>). This leads to a "hunched over" posture which brings the head forward, 
              causing the Trapezius (aka your "traps") and Pectorals (aka your "pecs") to tense up. </p>
        </div>
        <div class="image-row">
          <img class="long" src="images/shoulders/neck_illustration1a.jpg">
          <img class="long" src="images/shoulders/trapezius-pain.jpeg">
          <img class="short" src="images/shoulders/posture-correction.jpg">
        </div>
        <div class="top-box"> 
          <div class="text-div">
            <p> Forward Shoulders </p>
          </div>
          <div class="image-row">
            <img class="short" src="images/shoulders/vertical-sternum-pack.jpg">
            <img class="long" src="images/shoulders/super-straps2.jpg">
            {{!-- <img class="short" src="images/shoulders/.jpg"> --}}
          </div>
          <br/>
        </div>
        <div class="text-div">
          <p> Many forms of shoulder-related computer strain however, are usaually a result of tension 
              being held between the <a href="/neck-lean">neck</a> and <a href="/wrists">wrist</a>. 
              If either of these areas are strained, try correcting them and see if the pain persists. </p>
        </div>
        <div class="image-row">
          <img class="x-long" src="images/shoulders/shoulders1.jpg">
          <img class="long" src="images/shoulders/neck_tennis_elbow_pain_pattern.jpg">
          <img class="x-long" src="images/shoulders/Adult-Spine-radiculopathy-c6-c7.png">
        </div>
        <div class="text-div">
          <p> In particular, make sure your keyboard and mouse are not positioned too far in front of you,
              as this may contribute to a more "hunched" shoulders-forward posture.</p>
          <p> If you experience shoulder pain in the mouse-arm specifically, switching to a <b>vertical mouse</b> can often help. 
              By aligning the arm in a more neutral position, you can take much of the strain off of the internal rotator muscles.</p>
        </div>       
        <div class="image-row">
          <img class="x-long" src="images/shoulders/horizontal-mouse-posture.jpg">
          <img class="x-long" src="images/shoulders/vertical-mouse-posture.jpg">
        </div>
        <br/>
